interrogation2:
An investigation of those familiar with Henry, including the barista at the cat cafe, paint a picture of a sympathetic young man, though still not one that explains why he would steal the cats. Learning that he hasn't been seen for several days, Christina and the Chief go to the Public Security Bureau, where Christina attempts to argue for Henry's innocence. Her request for a more formal investigation is denied, with the reason given being that available resources should go towards cases with more tangible evidence, such as the antique theft incident, as opposed to those involving run-of-the-mill street thugs. Despite Christina's appeals to justice and equality in the eyes of the law, she and the Chief are left once more to take matters into their own hands.

A cursory search of Henry's apartment reveals that he's been spending a large portion of his welfare money on cat food for strays. They also discover his large collection of mystery novels. The two bring the food to his home-made cat shelter, finding not only the three missing cats, but a mysterious piece of graffiti. Christina then realizes that this is a trail left for them to follow. Once the two piece the clues together to form a specific address, they set out immediately.

//After a series of investigations, you discover that the real Henry is quite different from what you initially thought. There is more to this seemingly simple case of cat theft. You found the cats, but Henry is still missing. At the same time, you piece together the message he left you through the cat names: 4 Inkborough Street.//

interrogation3:
The pair find Henry tied up in a warehouse, surrounded by a businessman and a group of mercenaries. The mercenaries reveal that the antique theft case was actually a hoax set up to allow the businessman to profit from insurance fraud. Christina and the Chief leap into action, freeing Henry and subduing almost all of the suspects. The sole escapee is stopped by Henry and a squadron of police officers, called to the scene by a terminal that Henry received from the Chief. Despite his role in solving the case, Henry is still arrested for breaking and entering, an act that Christina decries. Henry reassures her that his sacrifice was worth it -- he finally got to play the detective role of his dreams, an accomplishment well worth a short jail sentence.

Later, Christina tells the Chief that she managed to use her connections not only to get Henry released, but to get him employed in the Public Security Bureau's  undercover program. She thanks the Chief for their help and asks them if they would be willing to serve as her assistant on her continued mission of uncovering the truth about Shalom. The Chief readily agrees, hoping to give her the closure she deserves.

//This complex, gray world needs idealists like Christina. She might seem a bit naive to others, but she resolutely believes in justice... The great detective and her little assistant will keep marching down the path of justice without waivering.//
